            <h3> <b>Thematic Areas</b> </h3>

           <p> 
          <ul>
          <li>
          <b>Fair, ethical and gender-responsive recruitment of OFWs</b> - Seventy percent of human trafficking victims assisted by the Department of Social Welfare and Development (DSWD) in 2020 were women.[1] Incidences of illegal recruitment and trafficking were expected to increase amid the economic impacts of COVID-19. How can this be avoided, and how do we ensure that women and other would-be migrant workers benefit from fair and ethical recruitment?
          </li><br>
          <li>
          <b>Decent work in destination countries for women OFWs</b> - Majority of women OFWs work in elementary occupations,[2] which include domestic work, where they receive low wages and limited social protection. Many of them work inside households, where work conditions are difficult to monitor. How can decent work be assured in these scenarios?
          </li><br>
          <li>
          <b>Sustainable and gender-responsive reintegration of returning OFWs</b> – The International Organization for Migration (IOM) defines sustainable reintegration as the point when a migrant worker has achieved “levels of economic self-sufficiency, social stability, and psychosocial well-being that make their further migration decisions a matter of choice, rather than necessity.”[3] How can we facilitate this for women OFWs or OFWs with diverse SOGIE?
          </li><br>
          <li>
          <b>Making labor migration more gender-responsive post-pandemic</b> – The COVID-19 pandemic revealed the unequal care burden of women and men, including the disproportionate representation of women in health and social care, where they comprise 70 percent of workers.[4] How can we translate this realization into action that will benefit women and gender nonconforming migrant workers?
          </li>


          </ul>

          
          </p>
